{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517773"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12836"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12836"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.46,0.31,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77302"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5279"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62809"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"3542"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"8831"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42823"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77302"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a four day history of severe and increasing pain and swelling in her neck. Over the last week she has felt tired, with a low-grade fever and generalised body ache, palpitations, headache and heat intolerance. Three weeks ago she had a sore throat that was resolved by taking medications prescribed by her GP. On examination her blood pressure is 153/101 mmHg, pulse 128/min and temperature: 37.8\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is a visible swelling in her anterior neck that is tender and moves on swallowing. Laboratory investigation results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EESR: 49mm/hr (0-30).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 55mg/L (\u0026lt;5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 145g/L (130-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeucocytes: 7.9 x 10^9 cells/L (4.0-11.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ET4: 54pmol/L (10-20).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ET3: 9.1pmol (3.1-4.5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETSH: 0.01mIU/L (0.5-4.5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum thyroid peroxidase: 19 IU/mL (\u0026lt;35).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to pain relief, which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Propylthiouracil","Propranolol","Carbimazole","Radioactive iodine therapy","Potassium iodide solution"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario has subacute thyroiditis (SAT), which is characterised by a painful and swollen thyroid gland along with generalised body ache, low-grade fever and signs and symptoms of hyperthyroidism initially. The best treatment option for subacute thyroiditis is a beta-blocker such as\u003Cstrong\u003E propranolol.\u003C/strong\u003E Symptomatic treatment consists of giving NSAIDs for the relief of pain and sometimes prednisolone in cases where the patient is not responding to NSAIDs. Beta-blockers help in relieving the signs and symptoms of thyrotoxicosis that occur in the initial phase of subacute thyroiditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropylthiouracil \u003C/strong\u003Eis an antithyroid drug that is used in the treatment of Graves\u0027 disease, toxic multinodular goitre, and toxic adenoma. Antithyroid drugs have no role in the management of established SAT as the excess thyroid hormone levels result from the release of preformed thyroxine and triiodothyronine from inflamed tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarbimazole \u003C/strong\u003Eis also an antithyroid drug that helps by decreasing the synthesis of thyroid hormone, but it is also not useful in SAT because there is no new production of thyroid hormone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadioactive iodine therapy\u003C/strong\u003E involves the administration of a radioactive isotope of iodine to destroy thyroid tissue. It is used rarely, primarily in the management of thyroid storm rather than in certain cases of hyperthyroidism\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium iodide solution\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Lugol\u0027s solution, is rarely used, primarily in the management of thyroid storm rather than in certain cases of hyperthyroidism. However, it is not a suitable long-term treatment option. It may provide temporary relief by inhibiting the release of thyroid hormones, but it does not address the underlying cause of hyperthyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Symptomatic treatment along with beta-blockers is the treatment of choice for subacute thyroiditis."],"references":["Hennessey Jv. Subacute Thyroiditis. [Updated 2018 Jun 12]. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279084/","Martinez Quintero B, Yazbeck C, Sweeney LB. Thyroiditis: Evaluation and Treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2021 Dec 1;104(6):609-617. PMID: 34913664.","Mundy-Baird G, Kyriacou A, Syed AA. De Quervain subacute thyroiditis. CMAJ. 2021 Jul 5;193(26):E1007. doi: 10.1503/cmaj.202787. PMID: 34226265; PMCID: PMC8248578."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62809"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12836"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62809"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:44:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:44:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5279"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77302"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name